}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s1\li360\fi-360\kerning24\fs56\lang1033\li0\fi0 {\f1\fs88\cf1 Problem: Monopoly /monopsony\par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s2\li1080\fi-360\kerning24\fs48\lang1033\li360 {\pntext\pard\plain\f3\fs56 \'95\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf3\pnfs56{\pntxtb \'95}}{\f2\fs56\cf1 Monopoly  practices threaten voluntariness of exchange by limiting options\par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s2\li1080\fi-360\kerning24\fs48\lang1033\li360 {\pntext\pard\plain\f3\fs56 \'95\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf3\pnfs56{\pntxtb \'95}}{\f2\fs56\cf1 If only one seller of food: \'93given my great need for food and the absence of alternatives, the seller is able to dictate the terms. In one sense I choose to make the deal, but the voluntariness of my choice is limited by the absence of alternatives. Just as the robber presented me with a very limited choice, so the conditions of control over the market limit my options\'94 [12]\par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s2\li1080\fi-360\kerning24\fs48\lang1033\li360 {\f2\fs56\cf1 \par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s1\li360\fi-360\kerning24\fs56\lang1033\li0\fi0 {\f1\fs88\cf1 Problem: Limiting perceived options\par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s2\li1080\fi-360\kerning24\fs48\lang1033\li360 {\pntext\pard\plain\f3\fs56 \'95\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf3\pnfs56{\pntxtb \'95}}{\f2\fs56\cf1 Seller can make it seem as though options are limited.\par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s2\li1080\fi-360\kerning24\fs48\lang1033\li360 {\pntext\pard\plain\f3\fs56 \'95\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf3\pnfs56{\pntxtb \'95}}{\f2\fs56\cf1 E.g., talking down other options et cetera\par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s2\li1080\fi-360\kerning24\fs48\lang1033\li360 {\pntext\pard\plain\f3\fs56 \'95\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf3\pnfs56{\pntxtb \'95}}{\f2\fs56\cf1 \'94With a convincing presentation, a customer might easily perceive the options to be very limited. Whether or not the technique is questionable may depend upon the accuracy of the perception. If the salesperson is attempting to take away a legitimate alternative, that is an attempt to undermine the customer\'92s voluntary choice.\'94 [12]\par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s2\li1080\fi-360\kerning24\fs48\lang1033\li360 {\f2\fs56\cf1 \par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s1\li360\fi-360\kerning24\fs56\lang1033\li0\fi0 {\f1\fs88\cf1 Problem: Concealing nature of interaction\par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s2\li1080\fi-360\kerning24\fs48\lang1033\li360 {\pntext\pard\plain\f3\fs56 \'95\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf3\pnfs56{\pntxtb \'95}}{\f2\fs56\cf1 Seller involving buyer in purchase by concealing the nature of the interaction\par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s2\li1080\fi-360\kerning24\fs48\lang1033\li360 {\pntext\pard\plain\f3\fs56 \'95\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf3\pnfs56{\pntxtb \'95}}{\f2\fs56\cf1 e.g., pretending to interview or conduct a contest; sending unsolicited products then billing\par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s2\li1080\fi-360\kerning24\fs48\lang1033\li360 {\pntext\pard\plain\f3\fs56 \'95\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf3\pnfs56{\pntxtb \'95}}{\f2\fs56\cf1 \'93The customer does not consciously choose to listen to a sales presentation, but finds that this is what is happening. Some psychological research suggests that when people do something which appears to commit them to a course of actions, even without choosing to do so, they will tend to act as though such a choice had been made\'85.if a salesperson successfully involves the customer in considering a purchase, the customer may feel committed to give serious thought to the matter.\'94 [13]\par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s1\li360\fi-360\kerning24\fs56\lang1033\li0\fi0 {\f1\fs88\cf1 Problematic tactics\par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s2\li1080\fi-360\kerning24\fs48\lang1033\li360 {\pntext\pard\plain\f3\fs56 \'95\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf3\pnfs56{\pntxtb \'95}}{\f2\fs56\cf1 Attempting to get around voluntary choice of customer.\par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s2\li1080\fi-360\kerning24\fs48\lang1033\li360 {\pntext\pard\plain\f3\fs56 \'95\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf3\pnfs56{\pntxtb \'95}}{\f2\fs56\cf1 Using misinformation to limit customer\'92s range of choices\par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s2\li1080\fi-360\kerning24\fs48\lang1033\li360 {\pntext\pard\plain\f3\fs56 \'95\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf3\pnfs56{\pntxtb \'95}}{\f2\fs56\cf1 Deceptions about:\par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s3\li1800\fi-360\kerning24\fs40\lang1033\li1080 {\pntext\pard\plain\f3\fs48 \'95\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf3\pnfs48{\pntxtb \'95}}{\f2\fs48\cf1 Purpose of encounter\par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s4\li2520\fi-360\kerning24\lang1033\li1800 {\pntext\pard\plain\f3\fs40 \'95\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf3\pnfs40{\pntxtb \'95}}{\f2\fs40\cf1 Attempts to get them to appear to commit to a course of action so that they will tend to act as if such a choice has been made to minimize cognitive dissonance.\par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s3\li1800\fi-360\kerning24\fs40\lang1033\li1080 {\pntext\pard\plain\f3\fs48 \'95\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf3\pnfs48{\pntxtb \'95}}{\f2\fs48\cf1 The presence of an obligation\par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s4\li2520\fi-360\kerning24\lang1033\li1800 {\pntext\pard\plain\f3\fs40 \'95\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf3\pnfs40{\pntxtb \'95}}{\f2\fs40\cf1 Case: Sending unsolicited books, then billing.\par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s3\li1800\fi-360\kerning24\fs40\lang1033\li1080 {\f2\fs48\cf1 \par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s1\li360\fi-360\kerning24\fs56\lang1033\li0\fi0 {\f1\fs120\cf1 Rationality condition\par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s1\li360\fi-360\kerning24\fs56\lang1033\li0\fi0 {\f1\fs88\cf1 Rationality condition\par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s2\li1080\fi-360\kerning24\fs48\lang1033\li360 {\pntext\pard\plain\f3\fs56 \'95\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf3\pnfs56{\pntxtb \'95}}{\f2\fs56\cf1 Voluntary exchange is unlikely if the customer is unable to make a rational judgment about the costs and benefits of a purchase.\par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s2\li1080\fi-360\kerning24\fs48\lang1033\li0\fi0 {\f2\fs56\cf1 \par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s2\li1080\fi-360\kerning24\fs48\lang1033\li360 {\f2\fs56\cf1 \par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s1\li360\fi-360\kerning24\fs56\lang1033\li0\fi0 {\f1\fs88\cf1 Rationality\par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s2\li1080\fi-360\kerning24\fs48\lang1033\li360 {\pntext\pard\plain\f3\fs56 \'95\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf3\pnfs56{\pntxtb \'95}}{\f2\fs56\cf1 \'93We could set the standards of rationality so high that very few exchanges would meet them. But for the purposes of this condition, we need not mean the absence of any non-rational or even irrational components in a decision. All that is required is for the individual to have a fairly accurate perception of the costs and benefits of an exchange in relation to personal needs and desires.\'94 [13]\par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s1\li360\fi-360\kerning24\fs56\lang1033\li0\fi0 {\f1\fs88\cf1 Subverting rationality\par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s2\li1080\fi-360\kerning24\fs48\lang1033\li360 {\pntext\pard\plain\f3\fs56 \'95\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf3\pnfs56{\pntxtb \'95}}{\f2\fs56\cf1 \'93The salesperson is not responsible for making a rational calculation for the customer, but when [she]...knowingly urges an action which is not beneficial to the consumer, that is in effect trying to get the customer to make an irrational judgment.\'94 [16]\par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s2\li1080\fi-360\kerning24\fs48\lang1033\li360 {\pntext\pard\plain\f3\fs56 \'95\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf3\pnfs56{\pntxtb \'95}}{\f2\fs56\cf1 \'93It is not the job of a salesperson to present all the facts as objectively as possible. But if playing  on a customer\'92s emotions is calculated to obscure the customer\'92s ability to make rational judgments about whether a purchase is in her best interest, then it is morally objectionable.\'94 [16]\par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s2\li1080\fi-360\kerning24\fs48\lang1033\li360 {\f2\fs56\cf1 \par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s1\li360\fi-360\kerning24\fs56\lang1033\li0\fi0 {\f1\fs88\cf1 Ability to make rational judgments depends on\par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s2\li1080\fi-360\kerning24\fs48\lang1033\li360 {\pntext\pard\plain\f3\fs56 \'95\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf3\pnfs56{\pntxtb \'95}}{\f2\fs56\cf1 Emotional control\par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s3\li1800\fi-360\kerning24\fs40\lang1033\li1080 {\pntext\pard\plain\f3\fs48 \'95\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf3\pnfs48{\pntxtb \'95}}{\f2\fs48\cf1 Desires / emotions can be irrational when they come into conflict \'93with needs or with other desires which are more central to personal satisfaction.\'94 [16]\par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s2\li1080\fi-360\kerning24\fs48\lang1033\li360 {\pntext\pard\plain\f3\fs56 \'95\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf3\pnfs56{\pntxtb \'95}}{\f2\fs56\cf1 Control over one\'92s desires\par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s3\li1800\fi-360\kerning24\fs40\lang1033\li1080 {\pntext\pard\plain\f3\fs48 \'95\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf3\pnfs48{\pntxtb \'95}}{\f2\fs48\cf1 Selling to an alcoholic by appealing to her addiction is not okay because it attempts to undermine the capacity for rational judgment.\par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s1\li360\fi-360\kerning24\fs56\lang1033\li0\fi0 {\f1\fs88\cf1 Emotional appeals\par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s2\li1080\fi-360\kerning24\fs48\lang1033\li360 {\pntext\pard\plain\f3\fs56 \'95\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf3\pnfs56{\pntxtb \'95}}{\f2\fs56\cf1 \'93The key to distinguishing between legitimate and illegitimate emotional appeals lies in whether the appeal clouds one\'92s ability to make a decision based on satisfaction of genuine needs and desires\'94 [15]\par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s2\li1080\fi-360\kerning24\fs48\lang1033\li360 {\pntext\pard\plain\f3\fs56 \'95\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf3\pnfs56{\pntxtb \'95}}{\f2\fs56\cf1 \'93The salesperson is not responsible for making a rational calculation for the customer, but when a salesperson knowingly urges an action which is not beneficial to the consumer, that is in effect trying to get the consumer to make an irrational judgment. Any techniques used to achieve this end would be attempts to subvert the conditions of mutually beneficial exchange.\'94 [16]\par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s1\li360\fi-360\kerning24\fs56\lang1033\li0\fi0 {\f1\fs88\cf1 Examples of violating rationality condition\par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s2\li1080\fi-360\kerning24\fs48\lang1033\li360 {\pntext\pard\plain\f3\fs56 \'95\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf3\pnfs56{\pntxtb \'95}}{\f2\fs56\cf1 Flattery and appeals to vanity\par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s3\li1800\fi-360\kerning24\fs40\lang1033\li1080 {\pntext\pard\plain\f3\fs48 \'95\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf3\pnfs48{\pntxtb \'95}}{\f2\fs48\cf1 Not necessarily problematic; only when plays on a weakness or when will be taken seriously.\par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s2\li1080\fi-360\kerning24\fs48\lang1033\li360 {\pntext\pard\plain\f3\fs56 \'95\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf3\pnfs56{\pntxtb \'95}}{\f2\fs56\cf1 Appeals to personal weaknesses\par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s3\li1800\fi-360\kerning24\fs40\lang1033\li1080 {\pntext\pard\plain\f3\fs48 \'95\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf3\pnfs48{\pntxtb \'95}}{\f2\fs48\cf1 Desires to fit in with peer group\par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s3\li1800\fi-360\kerning24\fs40\lang1033\li1080 {\f2\fs48\cf1 \par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s1\li360\fi-360\kerning24\fs56\lang1033\li0\fi0 {\f1\fs88\cf1 Overall claim\par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s2\li1080\fi-360\kerning24\fs48\lang1033\li360 {\pntext\pard\plain\f3\fs56 \'95\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf3\pnfs56{\pntxtb \'95}}{\f2\fs56\cf1 Rejects:\par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s3\li1800\fi-360\kerning24\fs40\lang1033\li1080 {\pntext\pard\plain\f3\fs48 \'95\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf3\pnfs48{\pntxtb \'95}}{\f2\fs48\cf1 Nonrational}{\f2\fs48\cf1  appeals are only objectionable if they are so strong that one could not reasonably be expected to resist them. \par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s3\li1800\fi-360\kerning24\fs40\lang1033\li1080 {\pntext\pard\plain\f3\fs48 \'95\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf3\pnfs48{\pntxtb \'95}}{\f2\fs48\cf1 \'93Even if the alcoholic might in some cases be expected to resist a temptation, it could still be morally objectionable to make an appeal which encourages her to do something harmful.\'94 [17]\par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s2\li1080\fi-360\kerning24\fs48\lang1033\li360 {\pntext\pard\plain\f3\fs56 \'95\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf3\pnfs56{\pntxtb \'95}}{\f2\fs56\cf1 Accepts: harmfulness matters.\par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s3\li1800\fi-360\kerning24\fs40\lang1033\li1080 {\pntext\pard\plain\f3\fs48 \'95\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf3\pnfs48{\pntxtb \'95}}{\f2\fs48\cf1 \'93But in cases where there are potentially significant gains or losses, the seller has a responsibility not to manipulate emotions or desires in ways which impair a customer\'92s pursuit of personal wellbeing. The greater the potential harm or benefit involved, the greater the seller\'92s responsibility.\'94 [17]\par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s1\li360\fi-360\kerning24\fs56\lang1033\li0\fi0 {\f1\fs120\cf1 Other \par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s1\li360\fi-360\kerning24\fs56\lang1033\li0\fi0 {\f1\fs88\cf1 What if the system encourages violations?\par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s2\li1080\fi-360\kerning24\fs48\lang1033\li360 {\pntext\pard\plain\f3\fs56 \'95\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf3\pnfs56{\pntxtb \'95}}{\f2\fs56\cf1 May mitigate individual moral responsibility\par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s2\li1080\fi-360\kerning24\fs48\lang1033\li360 {\pntext\pard\plain\f3\fs56 \'95\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf3\pnfs56{\pntxtb \'95}}{\f2\fs56\cf1 \'93If a system is abused so significantly that adhering to moral requirements demands great personal sacrifice, there may be little personal blame for the individual who chooses not to make the sacrifice. But in that case there is a general responsibility to alter the system so that it does not give rise to personal dilemmas of this kind.\'94[18]\par 
}\pard\plain\ltrpar\s1\li360\fi-360\kerning24\fs56\lang1033\li0\fi0 {\f1\fs120\cf1 Deception and withholding information in sales\par 
